The paper discusses the use of behavior trees (BTs) as a data structure for modeling medical procedures and clinical practice guidelines. This involves the integration of AI systems with clinical workflows, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper emphasizes the importance of human-readability and authoring tools, which suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use of BTs for modeling medical procedures also has implications for robotics (cs.RO) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the potential for automated treatment systems, which could fall under the category of cybernetics (cs.CY).
